WEBVTT

00:01.969 --> 00:03.102
[ Horn honks ]

00:03.104 --> 00:04.970
Man: Taxi!

00:04.972 --> 00:06.839
[ Horn honks ]

00:06.841 --> 00:08.173
♪♪

00:08.175 --> 00:11.477
[ Horns honking ]

00:21.489 --> 00:24.056
[ Tires screech ]

00:24.058 --> 00:25.591
Go around.

00:25.593 --> 00:26.692
[ Engine revving ]

00:26.694 --> 00:28.460
Go around!

00:28.462 --> 00:30.462
[ Tires screech ]

00:33.067 --> 00:35.667
What the hell's your problem?!
Go around!

00:38.072 --> 00:39.872
Shit!

00:39.874 --> 00:42.574
[ Panting ]

00:48.716 --> 00:50.749
[ Grunting ]

00:55.623 --> 00:58.090
[ Scraping ]

01:02.263 --> 01:03.996
[ Tires screech ]

01:03.998 --> 01:06.231
Buzz: That's it.
No shot of the car.

01:06.233 --> 01:09.668
Okay, Buzz, turn it off.

01:09.670 --> 01:12.771
♪♪

01:17.311 --> 01:18.677
[ Camera shutter clicks ]

01:18.679 --> 01:21.547
Oh.

01:21.549 --> 01:24.383
[ Sighs ]

01:25.419 --> 01:28.520
Distance from point of impact --
123 feet.

01:28.522 --> 01:30.189
That's a long way
to drag someone.

01:30.191 --> 01:32.458
Probably what our victim
thought, too.

01:34.161 --> 01:36.428
Chief.
Well, there's no doubt that

01:36.430 --> 01:38.330
this is a hit and run,
so Traffic will --

01:38.332 --> 01:40.132
Fritz: I know
it's a hit and run, Lieutenant.

01:40.134 --> 01:41.500
That's why you're here.

01:41.502 --> 01:42.901
Right now,
Los Angeles is having

01:42.903 --> 01:45.771
something of a war
between cars and bikes.

01:45.773 --> 01:49.174
We've become the number-one city
in the nation for hit and runs.

01:49.176 --> 01:50.609
Our Traffic division
is overwhelmed.

01:50.611 --> 01:52.177
Too few drivers
are getting arrested

01:52.179 --> 01:53.445
and too many children
are being killed.

01:53.447 --> 01:54.713
We have to turn that around.

01:54.715 --> 01:56.849
Starting tonight,
the hit-and-run situation

01:56.851 --> 01:59.318
has become a major crime.

01:59.320 --> 02:00.652
Tell your captain I'll be

02:00.654 --> 02:03.789
keeping up on the progress
of this case.

02:06.861 --> 02:08.660
Buzz: Well, I don't know
if it's a major crime,

02:08.662 --> 02:10.195
but I can say
from experience

02:10.197 --> 02:12.564
the car/bike thing
is a major problem.

02:12.566 --> 02:14.700
Provenza: Well, you should've
never sold your Prius,

02:14.702 --> 02:16.468
and you're gonna learn that
the hard way.

02:16.470 --> 02:19.138
[ Clears throat ]
All right, Kendall, T.O.D.

02:19.140 --> 02:21.073
An hour ago, tops.

02:21.075 --> 02:22.407
Cause of death could be

02:22.409 --> 02:24.443
the massive fracture
to the back of the skull

02:24.445 --> 02:27.045
or the two tons of automobile
that cracked his ribs,

02:27.047 --> 02:28.480
maybe piercing a lung.

02:28.482 --> 02:30.549
Or it might be that
the pain of having his leg

02:30.551 --> 02:33.018
nearly severed from his body
induced cardiac arrest.

02:33.020 --> 02:34.720
I...can't say.

02:34.722 --> 02:36.355
It's --
It's all right, Kendall.

02:36.357 --> 02:38.123
It's, uh --
it's all right.

02:38.125 --> 02:40.893
We'll, uh, get the details
from Morales.

02:40.895 --> 02:42.427
Sorry if I, uh --

02:42.429 --> 02:43.762
two months ago,
my teenage cousin

02:43.764 --> 02:45.964
was riding his bike
on Venice Boulevard

02:45.966 --> 02:48.267
and he...

02:49.904 --> 02:51.503
Excuse me.

02:51.505 --> 02:54.606
♪♪

02:56.644 --> 02:59.211
All right, uh, Amy,
what do we know?

02:59.213 --> 03:02.714
Our victim is William Sax,
24, USC law student.

03:02.716 --> 03:04.683
Apparently heading home
from school

03:04.685 --> 03:07.319
when he made a wrong turn
under someone's car.

03:07.321 --> 03:10.189
Um,
his last text from Cliff.

03:10.191 --> 03:11.890
"This isn't over.
I'll beat your ass."

03:11.892 --> 03:14.326
Well, we may get Cliff
for two charges --

03:14.328 --> 03:17.796
vehicular manslaughter
and texting while driving.

03:17.798 --> 03:19.164
Tao.

03:19.166 --> 03:20.732
Victim has
no driver's license,

03:20.734 --> 03:23.402
but he's got
a state-issued I.D. card.

03:23.404 --> 03:25.504
Sanchez:
Sir, not done yet outside,

03:25.506 --> 03:27.272
but the driver
never stopped.

03:27.274 --> 03:29.274
No trace of skid marks
on the street.

03:29.276 --> 03:31.276
This bike is jacked up.

03:31.278 --> 03:33.378
See here?
Paint was scraped off.

03:33.380 --> 03:34.646
So when we find
the right vehicle,

03:34.648 --> 03:36.448
this color's gonna be
on it somewhere.

03:36.450 --> 03:39.318
Look at that. Bright bike,
reflectors everywhere,

03:39.320 --> 03:40.752
on his helmet and shoes.

03:40.754 --> 03:42.888
He'd have to be hard to miss,
even at night.

03:42.890 --> 03:45.691
Either a drunk confused
the gas pedal with the brakes,

03:45.693 --> 03:48.093
or someone really
hates bicycles.

03:48.095 --> 03:49.795
We found this
near the impact.

03:49.797 --> 03:51.763
Could be a piece of
the vehicle's headlight.

03:51.765 --> 03:54.333
All right,
we know that we're standing

03:54.335 --> 03:56.602
30, 40 minutes from USC,

03:56.604 --> 03:58.804
so while we finish up here,

03:58.806 --> 04:01.640
Mike, you and Buzz,
see if you can figure

04:01.642 --> 04:04.776
how our young Mr. William Sax
got here tonight.

04:04.778 --> 04:06.278
Maybe his GoPro
could tell us.

04:06.280 --> 04:08.046
Or his cell.

04:08.048 --> 04:09.681
Ah.

04:09.683 --> 04:12.784
♪♪

04:14.588 --> 04:16.655
Mason: So, even though he didn't
use his phone on the bike,

04:16.657 --> 04:18.857
Will Sax received several alerts
from sports apps

04:18.859 --> 04:20.058
while he was riding home,

04:20.060 --> 04:22.527
allowing us to ping his cell
and trace his path.

04:22.529 --> 04:24.329
And it matches with the video,
sir.

04:24.331 --> 04:27.132
Mike, how are we doing
slowing down the GoPro?

04:27.134 --> 04:29.635
I should be able to I.D. some
vehicle plates in a minute.

04:29.637 --> 04:32.504
Okay. What else do we know
about Will Sax?

04:32.506 --> 04:35.274
Not much. No criminal record,
no traffic citations,

04:35.276 --> 04:37.009
no vehicle registered
in his name.

04:37.011 --> 04:38.343
Hmm, imagine that.

04:38.345 --> 04:40.379
Anti-automobile
and living in L.A.

04:40.381 --> 04:42.481
Well, he was also studying
environmental law.

04:42.483 --> 04:45.050
Maybe he didn't drive to
minimize his carbon footprint.

04:45.052 --> 04:47.686
Otherwise, he's on Facebook
and Instagram.

04:47.688 --> 04:49.221
Pretty typical millennial.

04:49.223 --> 04:52.157
His relationship status
says he's engaged to Indra Kane.

04:52.159 --> 04:53.525
Also a USC law student,

04:53.527 --> 04:55.360
and she does have
a driver's license.

04:55.362 --> 04:57.663
Address matches the one
on the victim's I.D.

04:57.665 --> 04:59.931
Sharon: Amy, if you could call
Lieutenant Provenza

04:59.933 --> 05:01.199
and ask him to start

05:01.201 --> 05:04.036
the notification process
with Ms. Kane.

05:04.038 --> 05:05.871
Yes, ma'am.

05:05.873 --> 05:07.506
Good work, everyone.

05:07.508 --> 05:09.574
If we can solve this hit and run
in a couple of days,

05:09.576 --> 05:11.576
it is a win for us all.

05:11.578 --> 05:14.546
Yeah, at the risk of
irritating everyone,

05:14.548 --> 05:17.249
this was a hit,
not a hit and run.

05:17.251 --> 05:19.017
-What?
-Driver never stopped.

05:19.019 --> 05:21.920
Tapped William twice,
scared him onto another street,

05:21.922 --> 05:23.555
and followed him
around the corner.

05:23.557 --> 05:26.391
No sign of skid marks,
so no attempt at braking.

05:26.393 --> 05:29.695
No damage to another vehicle,
clean escape.

05:29.697 --> 05:31.697
Too controlled
for a drunk driver.

05:31.699 --> 05:34.900
Maybe our victim pissed off
some motorist along the way.

05:34.902 --> 05:37.202
Let's not make mountains out of
mole hills, Lieutenant.

05:37.204 --> 05:39.938
Andy has some valuable points,
Chief.

05:39.940 --> 05:41.740
If there was intent
behind this death --

05:41.742 --> 05:43.175
But don't force it
into a murder

05:43.177 --> 05:44.976
just because that's what
you're used to over here.

05:44.978 --> 05:46.978
Let's keep calling it
a hit and run

05:46.980 --> 05:49.981
till we can prove otherwise,
as risky as that is.

05:52.286 --> 05:56.888
Uh, Buzz, does the victim's
fiancée have a Facebook page?

05:56.890 --> 05:58.557
Uh, right here.

05:58.559 --> 06:02.060
So, what are you thinking?
It's always the fiancée?

06:02.062 --> 06:03.862
No, I'm thinking about
whether or not

06:03.864 --> 06:07.966
Indra will be able to help us
before she falls apart.

06:07.968 --> 06:09.801
Indra: I was on the verge
of calling you.

06:09.803 --> 06:11.570
Do you know
where Will is?

06:11.572 --> 06:16.708
Well, um, to that end, Ms. Kane,
we really need your help.

06:16.710 --> 06:18.276
We just have
a few questions.

06:18.278 --> 06:19.745
Anything, anything.
Please.

06:19.747 --> 06:21.279
What do you
want to know?

06:21.281 --> 06:22.714
Does your fiancé --

06:22.716 --> 06:25.784
Does Will ride his bike a lot,
ma'am?

06:25.786 --> 06:26.918
Everywhere.

06:26.920 --> 06:28.587
He doesn't have
a driver's license.

06:28.589 --> 06:31.123
Now, I know law schools
are expensive,

06:31.125 --> 06:34.526
but you two seem to be
doing fine, though.

06:34.528 --> 06:36.995
Will's family has
a little bit of money.

06:36.997 --> 06:39.498
He pays for law school through
a fund his parents set up,

06:39.500 --> 06:41.500
and both of my parents
are doctors.

06:41.502 --> 06:44.669
So, uh, Will's parents
have a fund?

06:44.671 --> 06:46.138
I guess it's called
a foundation.

06:46.140 --> 06:48.607
Will's dad's the CFO
of a pharmaceutical company

06:48.609 --> 06:51.510
and his mom's a broker
with a Wall Street firm.

06:51.512 --> 06:52.978
Why is this important?

06:52.980 --> 06:56.181
Does Will ride home the same way
every night, ma'am?

06:56.183 --> 06:57.849
Yes.
Pretty much.

06:57.851 --> 06:59.484
Does --
Does he have enemies?

06:59.486 --> 07:01.019
-No, no.
-Anybody who didn't like him?

07:01.021 --> 07:03.221
There's a young man named Cliff.
Did he ever complain --

07:03.223 --> 07:04.856
Oh, my God.

07:04.858 --> 07:06.525
No, he doesn't complain
about Cliff.

07:06.527 --> 07:07.959
They're best friends.

07:07.961 --> 07:09.594
Is Cliff okay?

07:09.596 --> 07:10.929
What happened?

07:10.931 --> 07:13.665
Did Will ever mention problems
with cars?

07:13.667 --> 07:16.368
Drivers getting angry at
sharing the road with his bike?

07:16.370 --> 07:18.336
Oh,
I-I remember a few days ago,

07:18.338 --> 07:19.738
I think
it was last Wednesday.

07:19.740 --> 07:21.239
Yeah,
it was last Wednesday.

07:21.241 --> 07:23.675
Will said he felt like
this car was following him.

07:23.677 --> 07:25.043
He said he saw it
a few times --

07:25.045 --> 07:27.446
on Vermont, at school,
near here.

07:27.448 --> 07:29.548
Did he mention
the type of car it was?

07:29.550 --> 07:31.917
Maybe. [ Sighs ]
I don't remember.

07:31.919 --> 07:34.119
I thought
he was being paranoid.

07:34.121 --> 07:37.222
♪♪

07:41.995 --> 07:43.762
-Ms. Kane.
-[ Crying ]No, no.

07:43.764 --> 07:45.130
-Sorry to inform you --
-No, don't!

07:45.132 --> 07:46.565
...but your fiancé, Will,
was --
No, he's fine.

07:46.567 --> 07:48.033
Look, I need you to
stop talking.

07:48.035 --> 07:51.002
-...involved in a --
-Look, I said stop talking!

07:51.004 --> 07:53.271
No, no.

07:53.273 --> 07:54.473
Have a seat.
It's all right.

07:54.475 --> 07:55.907
No.

07:55.909 --> 07:57.576
Please, stop.

07:57.578 --> 07:59.110
-It's okay.
-Please.

07:59.112 --> 08:03.548
Oh, my God, no.

08:03.550 --> 08:05.484
Will.

08:05.486 --> 08:08.520
Will.

08:08.522 --> 08:11.056
Will.

08:15.596 --> 08:17.262
Flynn:
Okay. Here you go.

08:17.264 --> 08:18.797
Wait until you try this.

08:18.799 --> 08:22.100
It's flourless, gluten-free,
sugar-free,

08:22.102 --> 08:25.437
and only about 80 calories
per serving. And --

08:25.439 --> 08:28.306
Devoid of any joy
relating to cake.

08:28.308 --> 08:30.876
Patrice: Don't knock it
before you've tried it, Louie,

08:30.878 --> 08:33.311
especially since
Andy made it himself

08:33.313 --> 08:35.714
for tonight
as we celebrate.

08:35.716 --> 08:38.683
Yes, yes.
Well, uh, thank you, Andy.

08:38.685 --> 08:42.153
Oh, and -- and congratulations
on your engagement.

08:42.155 --> 08:44.556
I knew you'd get around to it
eventually.

08:44.558 --> 08:46.691
Here you go.
This is about the most

08:46.693 --> 08:49.160
guilt-free dessert
I've ever made.

08:51.832 --> 08:53.298
So?

08:53.300 --> 08:54.399
What do you think?

08:54.401 --> 08:57.168
Ye gods.
Captain.

08:57.170 --> 08:59.137
It isn't too late
to call the whole thing off.

08:59.139 --> 09:02.607
I mean, no one will think less
of you, least of all me.

09:02.609 --> 09:04.175
Sharon: No.

09:04.177 --> 09:07.546
I really am getting excited
about the whole process.

09:09.383 --> 09:10.782
I mean, [chuckles]

09:10.784 --> 09:12.751
even the difficult moments

09:12.753 --> 09:15.320
[swallows]
are extremely rewarding.

09:15.322 --> 09:19.858
[ Chuckles ] Well, Andy, I think
your dessert is wonderful,

09:19.860 --> 09:21.826
and I've gotten to
the place where if I eat

09:21.828 --> 09:23.461
anything richer than this,

09:23.463 --> 09:24.629
I'll wake up
in the middle of the night

09:24.631 --> 09:26.064
and I can't
get back to sleep.

09:26.066 --> 09:29.601
And only one of us
needs to be doing that.

09:29.603 --> 09:31.670
So, if you'll excuse me.

09:31.672 --> 09:33.071
Honey,
where are you going?

09:33.073 --> 09:35.240
Oh, I'm just gonna
get a little fresh air.

09:35.242 --> 09:38.143
Oh, I'm so full.

09:38.145 --> 09:40.545
[ Chuckles ]

09:40.547 --> 09:41.746
Rusty: Napa?

09:41.748 --> 09:43.815
Your boss
is really spreading out.

09:43.817 --> 09:47.419
And he's pretty successful
for a 28 year old.

09:48.355 --> 09:50.722
Well, he's just never around
when I stop by,

09:50.724 --> 09:52.958
so I-I-I looked him up
online.

09:53.727 --> 09:55.627
No,
I'm not following him.

09:56.897 --> 09:58.697
Don't mind me.
I'm not listening.

09:58.699 --> 10:01.900
Uh, Gus, let me, uh --
let me call you back.

10:01.902 --> 10:03.702
Okay.

10:03.704 --> 10:06.638
Hey, Lieutenant.
What's up?

10:06.640 --> 10:09.841
I'm overdosing
on weddings.

10:09.843 --> 10:11.910
[ Chuckles ]
Even the happy ones,

10:11.912 --> 10:14.846
of which
there are too few.

10:14.848 --> 10:17.082
That sounds work-related.

10:17.084 --> 10:18.650
It is.

10:18.652 --> 10:20.085
Um, I'll explain.

10:20.087 --> 10:22.954
Usually --
n-not always --

10:22.956 --> 10:24.923
not the girls
who are raped,

10:24.925 --> 10:27.759
not the children
who are molested,

10:27.761 --> 10:32.197
but usually victims
are killed for a reason.

10:32.199 --> 10:35.600
They may have made
bad decisions, got greedy,

10:35.602 --> 10:38.103
stole somebody else's spouse,
dealt drugs,

10:38.105 --> 10:41.406
but not the kid that we found
last night.

10:41.408 --> 10:43.174
No.

10:43.176 --> 10:45.910
Will Sax had no enemies.

10:45.912 --> 10:47.412
Was a straight "A" student.

10:47.414 --> 10:51.149
He -- He was dedicated
to doing good in the world,

10:51.151 --> 10:54.786
and to find the body
of a young man like that,

10:54.788 --> 10:59.591
dragged over 40 yards
down a city street...

10:59.593 --> 11:01.159
[ Footsteps approaching ]

11:01.161 --> 11:03.261
Louie?
Come back inside.

11:03.263 --> 11:04.963
Sharon and Andy
want us to help them

11:04.965 --> 11:06.297
pick out
their wedding invitations.

11:06.299 --> 11:07.332
Ah.

11:07.334 --> 11:09.034
I'm not asking.

11:12.139 --> 11:13.772
Provenza:
Wedding invitations.

11:13.774 --> 11:16.875
You know,
I saw one earlier this morning.

11:16.877 --> 11:19.744
Makes me want to
jump over this railing.

11:19.746 --> 11:22.447
[ Chuckles ]
With your glass half full,

11:22.449 --> 11:23.948
a bottle of wine
in your hand,

11:23.950 --> 11:26.184
and Patrice here
to drive you home?

11:29.089 --> 11:30.188
You're right.

11:30.190 --> 11:32.190
You're right.

11:34.528 --> 11:36.561
How'd you get to know me
so well?

11:36.563 --> 11:39.864
♪♪

11:42.502 --> 11:44.736
Sykes: Doesn't look as if
the victim had anything to hide.

11:44.738 --> 11:46.838
Will Sax was
something of an open book

11:46.840 --> 11:48.406
with no bad marks in it.

11:48.408 --> 11:50.875
Well, his Facebook page
is free of haters and trolls.

11:50.877 --> 11:52.077
Just lots of likes.

11:52.079 --> 11:53.545
What about his parents,
Julio?

11:53.547 --> 11:55.714
Zora and Fredrick. We didn't
get much out of them, ma'am.

11:55.716 --> 11:57.248
We told her not to,

11:57.250 --> 12:00.518
but Will's fiancé called his mom
and dad before I got there.

12:00.520 --> 12:02.020
They took it really hard.

12:02.022 --> 12:04.122
I asked them to come in
as soon as possible,

12:04.124 --> 12:06.224
but since we're not allowed
to call it a murder...

12:06.226 --> 12:09.027
Yes.
What have we discovered,

12:09.029 --> 12:12.263
uh, about the vehicle that
ran Will off the road?

12:12.265 --> 12:14.833
Uh, good news, bad news
on the headlight piece.

12:14.835 --> 12:17.135
Good news,
we know it's an SUV

12:17.137 --> 12:21.272
made by either Chevy or GMC
between the years 2000 and 2006.

12:21.274 --> 12:22.974
Bad news,
that leaves about

12:22.976 --> 12:24.776
a couple hundred thousand
possibilities

12:24.778 --> 12:25.977
in southern California
alone.

12:25.979 --> 12:27.746
What about
Will's law school?

12:27.748 --> 12:29.948
Any problems there?
-Maybe, maybe.

12:29.950 --> 12:31.483
I spoke to the Dean.

12:31.485 --> 12:33.651
Will recently interviewed for,
and then last Friday,

12:33.653 --> 12:36.154
received a clerkship with the
9th District Court of Appeals.

12:36.156 --> 12:38.123
Huh.
That's pretty prestigious.

12:38.125 --> 12:40.091
And USC
is a top-20 law school.

12:40.093 --> 12:42.260
Throw in a clerkship
for a federal judge,

12:42.262 --> 12:44.262
Will could've joined
any law firm he liked,

12:44.264 --> 12:45.964
or have kicked off
a political career.

12:45.966 --> 12:47.198
And that's motive how?

12:47.200 --> 12:48.433
The runner-up
for that clerkship --

12:48.435 --> 12:50.502
Will's best friend,
Cliff Rainier.

12:50.504 --> 12:53.004
Sykes: Cliff texted last night
that this wasn't over

12:53.006 --> 12:54.472
and he was gonna
beat Will's ass.

12:54.474 --> 12:56.474
Losing out a clerkship
to your best friend?

12:56.476 --> 12:59.844
It's an unusual motive,
but people have killed for less.

12:59.846 --> 13:02.147
Yeah.
Jealousy's my favorite motive.

13:02.149 --> 13:05.216
Well, except for
infidelity and greed.

13:05.218 --> 13:09.053
Greed is my favorite,
favorite motive.

13:10.357 --> 13:12.056
Cliff: There were
no hard feelings because

13:12.058 --> 13:14.793
I knew it was going to be Will
from the moment he applied.

13:14.795 --> 13:16.461
Not anymore.

13:16.463 --> 13:18.363
No.

13:18.365 --> 13:20.298
Look, losing a good friend

13:20.300 --> 13:22.500
is not the right way
to get a clerkship.

13:22.502 --> 13:24.402
[ Sighs ]

13:24.404 --> 13:25.470
Poor Indra.

13:25.472 --> 13:27.972
And his parents,
it's like a nightmare.

13:27.974 --> 13:30.942
But you'll still take the gig.
You were runner-up.

13:30.944 --> 13:32.811
<i> I was a distant second,</i>
<i> I promise.</i>

13:32.813 --> 13:34.212
This kid
is really a suspect?

13:34.214 --> 13:35.914
Why?
<i> -Just happened, right?</i>

13:35.916 --> 13:37.715
Hold on a moment, Chief.
Just...
Sanchez:<i> The clerkship,</i>

13:37.717 --> 13:40.218
<i> you two were still</i>
<i> going back and forth over it,</i>

13:40.220 --> 13:41.719
arguing
the night he died.

13:41.721 --> 13:43.988
Arguing?
I wouldn't say that, no.

13:43.990 --> 13:45.857
The night he...

13:45.859 --> 13:47.525
It's so hard to say this.

13:47.527 --> 13:52.063
The night Will died,
we had been studying together.

13:52.065 --> 13:53.765
We went for a drink
when we finished,

13:53.767 --> 13:54.933
but there was no argument.

13:54.935 --> 13:57.402
Okay.
What were you not arguing about?

13:57.404 --> 14:00.939
Because the text you sent him
afterwards sound heated.

14:00.941 --> 14:03.174
"You backstabbing douche.
This isn't over.

14:03.176 --> 14:05.210
I'll beat your ass."
-That's not an argument?

14:05.212 --> 14:07.745
No. No, that's just the way
we talk to each other.

14:07.747 --> 14:09.848
Load more texts.
You'll see.

14:10.684 --> 14:12.183
We were just
kidding around.

14:12.185 --> 14:14.752
-Kidding about what?
-Is this really important

14:14.754 --> 14:16.321
in your investigation
of an accident?

14:16.323 --> 14:18.189
Why do you think
we read you your rights?

14:18.191 --> 14:19.724
Are you saying you'd like to
remain silent?

14:19.726 --> 14:20.992
Because
that's suspicious.

14:20.994 --> 14:22.994
Or do you want to
let us in on the joke?

14:22.996 --> 14:25.763
<i> Yeah. You were kidding.</i>
<i> Let's hear the joke.</i>

14:25.765 --> 14:28.066
Prepare
to laugh your asses off.

14:28.068 --> 14:30.101
<i> It was on the Judge Holly</i>
<i> clerkship thing.</i>

14:30.103 --> 14:33.071
<i> She's big on diversity,</i>
<i> and I asked Will if --</i>

14:33.073 --> 14:36.174
<i> when he went in for his</i>
<i> interview, I asked him if...</i>

14:36.176 --> 14:39.244
if he mentioned he was black,
and he laughed

14:39.246 --> 14:42.747
because we, like, both knew that
she already had two white clerks

14:42.749 --> 14:45.717
and the system
sort of requires,

14:45.719 --> 14:46.951
you know...

14:46.953 --> 14:48.786
What system would that be?

14:48.788 --> 14:50.321
-The system.
<i> -Quotas.</i>

14:50.323 --> 14:51.723
<i> -Like, racial quotas?</i>
-My least favorite motive.

14:51.725 --> 14:53.024
<i> There's no racial quotas.</i>

14:53.026 --> 14:54.659
Look, you're a lot older,
and Will and I,

14:54.661 --> 14:57.762
we didn't look at race the same
way the older generation does.

14:57.764 --> 14:59.297
Uh-huh.

14:59.299 --> 15:02.000
So, where did your "douche bag"
and "I'll beat your ass"

15:02.002 --> 15:04.402
come from if it was all
just fun and games?

15:04.404 --> 15:06.537
Your question is not pertinent
to a hit and run.

15:06.539 --> 15:07.906
Oh, it's pertinent.

15:07.908 --> 15:09.574
Right after
you sent this text to Will,

15:09.576 --> 15:12.610
he was mowed over and dragged
40 yards down a street.

15:12.612 --> 15:14.445
What I said had nothing
to do with that.

15:14.447 --> 15:16.314
If it was all okay,
then tell us

15:16.316 --> 15:18.116
the rest of your funny
conversation

15:18.118 --> 15:20.184
about the clerkship.

15:20.186 --> 15:21.753
Fine.

15:21.755 --> 15:23.454
I said Will should start a
movement

15:23.456 --> 15:27.025
saying Black Jobs Matter,
which was a joke

15:27.027 --> 15:29.961
because we both interned
for Judge Holly that summer.

15:29.963 --> 15:32.597
She knew us,
me especially, my family.

15:32.599 --> 15:34.198
Do you want me to go on?

15:34.200 --> 15:36.367
Please.
This is hilarious.

15:37.671 --> 15:41.072
And then I told him he had
middle-class white boy eyes,

15:41.074 --> 15:43.041
and he said
<i> he wasn't really middle class</i>

15:43.043 --> 15:44.575
<i> because his family's,</i>
<i> like, loaded.</i>

15:44.577 --> 15:46.477
<i> And I asked him what</i>
<i> country club he belonged to</i>

15:46.479 --> 15:49.347
<i>if he was so rich, and how come</i>
<i> I beat him at golf last week?</i>

15:49.349 --> 15:52.116
And he said his golf game was
usually way better than mine,

15:52.118 --> 15:54.585
and that's what the texts
were about, okay? Golf!

15:54.587 --> 15:57.255
And if you want to know why
Will really got the clerkship,

15:57.257 --> 15:59.490
it's probably because
he wrote this insanely good,

15:59.492 --> 16:00.925
very personal essay!

16:00.927 --> 16:02.760
I didn't read it,
but Judge Holly told him

16:02.762 --> 16:05.296
<i> that was a deal clincher,</i>
<i> and I believe her!</i>

16:05.298 --> 16:08.333
So, does he think that
he lost out on the clerkship

16:08.335 --> 16:11.035
because of race or not?

16:11.037 --> 16:12.637
Or does
why he lost matter?

16:12.639 --> 16:15.173
I mean, however you slice it,
he didn't get the job.

16:15.175 --> 16:16.808
<i> Screw the clerkship!</i>

16:16.810 --> 16:19.110
<i> Who cares about it now?</i>

16:19.112 --> 16:20.511
It was an accident.

16:20.513 --> 16:23.648
You're looking for someone
to blame, try the driver!

16:23.650 --> 16:25.016
Or look in the mirror.

16:25.018 --> 16:27.151
What a great job
the LAPD's doing right now

16:27.153 --> 16:28.820
protecting our streets.

16:28.822 --> 16:31.289
Am I under arrest?

16:32.492 --> 16:34.158
Am I?

16:38.164 --> 16:40.631
[ Door slams ]

16:41.301 --> 16:43.401
Anything about this kid
screaming murder?

16:43.403 --> 16:44.769
Because
I-I don't hear it.

16:44.771 --> 16:46.604
It will take longer
than you want, Chief,

16:46.606 --> 16:51.209
but I think that we need to
appeal to a federal judge.

16:52.178 --> 16:54.746
I can't tell you
how deeply saddened I was

16:54.748 --> 16:56.514
to hear about this.

16:56.516 --> 17:00.284
William Sax was
an extraordinary young man.

17:00.286 --> 17:02.253
If you came to me
30 years from now

17:02.255 --> 17:05.823
and asked about Will Sax,
Supreme Court Justice,

17:05.825 --> 17:07.458
I would not bat an eye.

17:07.460 --> 17:10.161
What do you know
about his friends?

17:10.163 --> 17:11.863
Provenza:
Like Cliff Rainier.

17:11.865 --> 17:14.732
We understand that
both boys interned for you.

17:14.734 --> 17:17.935
Uh, how was Cliff's relationship
with Will?

17:17.937 --> 17:20.271
They were
exceptionally close.

17:20.273 --> 17:23.641
In another era, they might've
started a firm together.

17:23.643 --> 17:28.346
And yet you picked Will Sax
to clerk, not Cliff.

17:28.348 --> 17:29.380
I did.

17:29.382 --> 17:31.282
I've known Cliff
since he was a child.

17:31.284 --> 17:33.117
He's a wonderful young man.

17:33.119 --> 17:34.752
Funny, entertaining,

17:34.754 --> 17:36.821
maybe going to be richer
than all of us.

17:36.823 --> 17:38.523
But he's not Will Sax.

17:38.525 --> 17:40.825
Not as smart?
Not a natural?

17:40.827 --> 17:42.060
No.

17:42.062 --> 17:45.196
Cliff is every bit of that
and more.

17:45.198 --> 17:47.999
But like a lot of
other young people,

17:48.001 --> 17:51.035
Cliff is mainly
interested in Cliff.

17:51.037 --> 17:53.738
Will had a genuine
desire to serve --

17:53.740 --> 17:55.106
feeding the homeless,

17:55.108 --> 17:58.309
mentoring at-risk boys,
Habitat for Humanity.

17:58.311 --> 18:00.111
You name it,
Will did it.

18:00.113 --> 18:02.280
And his essay.

18:02.282 --> 18:05.750
The essay he wrote...

18:05.752 --> 18:06.984
♪♪

18:06.986 --> 18:09.754
The attendant irony
is staggering.

18:09.756 --> 18:12.023
What irony?

18:12.025 --> 18:15.426
That he died
in a kind of car accident.

18:16.763 --> 18:18.196
That's ironic how?

18:18.198 --> 18:21.099
Because it was also
a car accident

18:21.101 --> 18:22.934
that altered Will's life.

18:22.936 --> 18:27.772
I actually suggested he get the
story published or posted

18:27.774 --> 18:30.208
because it provided
such a -- a great example

18:30.210 --> 18:31.843
of how one could turn trauma
and guilt --

18:31.845 --> 18:33.144
I-I'm sorry.

18:33.146 --> 18:37.415
What...accident
are you talking about?

18:37.417 --> 18:38.850
Oh.

18:38.852 --> 18:40.151
You don't know?

18:40.153 --> 18:41.419
Know what?

18:41.421 --> 18:44.155
When he was 16 years old,

18:44.157 --> 18:47.358
Will Sax ran over
another teenage boy

18:47.360 --> 18:49.360
and killed him.

19:01.574 --> 19:04.509
Louie.
What's the matter?

19:04.511 --> 19:06.210
What makes you think
anything's the matter?

19:06.212 --> 19:07.879
You haven't turned on
the television,

19:07.881 --> 19:10.214
you're not complaining about
putting stamps

19:10.216 --> 19:11.749
on those envelopes
for Sharon and Andy,

19:11.751 --> 19:14.852
and you haven't even taken
so much as a sip of your wine.

19:14.854 --> 19:16.287
So come on.
What's up?

19:16.289 --> 19:19.056
Well, I think

19:19.058 --> 19:20.525
that I need to
quit my job.

19:20.527 --> 19:23.027
[ Chuckling ]
Yeah, right.

19:23.029 --> 19:24.962
I'm serious, Patrice.

19:24.964 --> 19:26.731
I'm going to retire.

19:26.733 --> 19:29.133
Maybe next week.

19:29.135 --> 19:30.368
Is it this case?

19:30.370 --> 19:32.303
It's this kid.

19:32.305 --> 19:33.671
Everybody loved him.

19:33.673 --> 19:35.673
He was smart,
he was driven.

19:35.675 --> 19:40.912
He was just picked for
a clerkship to a federal judge,

19:40.914 --> 19:42.547
and then as it turns out,

19:42.549 --> 19:45.449
that choice was based
on an essay

19:45.451 --> 19:49.520
that our golden boy
completely fabricated

19:49.522 --> 19:53.157
with a story about running over
an 18-year-old kid

19:53.159 --> 19:54.892
and killing him.

19:54.894 --> 19:56.460
Are you sure
that he lied?

19:56.462 --> 20:01.032
We spent hours trying to track
down this so-called accident

20:01.034 --> 20:04.101
because the supposed victim
was also young,

20:04.103 --> 20:06.304
and revenge finally --

20:06.306 --> 20:09.840
finally,
revenge might have

20:09.842 --> 20:14.111
given some sense
to this senselessness.

20:14.113 --> 20:16.447
But his fiancée,

20:16.449 --> 20:20.451
she had never heard about
Will running over anyone.

20:20.453 --> 20:22.787
His best friend
had never heard about it,

20:22.789 --> 20:27.858
and Will Sax's name
appeared not one time

20:27.860 --> 20:32.196
on one accident report
over the last 10 years.

20:32.198 --> 20:34.832
Well [sighs]
what do his parents say?

20:34.834 --> 20:37.635
Well, they were too devastated
to come in the next day,

20:37.637 --> 20:40.838
and because we had publicly
stated it was a hit and run,

20:40.840 --> 20:42.106
we have to wait

20:42.108 --> 20:45.810
until they're emotionally
strong enough to talk.

20:45.812 --> 20:47.845
And...

20:47.847 --> 20:48.946
And?

20:48.948 --> 20:51.182
Well, there's going to be
someone new

20:51.184 --> 20:54.719
as the Assistant Chief
of the LAPD,

20:54.721 --> 20:56.354
and if it's not
Sharon Raydor,

20:56.356 --> 20:57.788
Major Crimes
could just go away.

20:57.790 --> 21:00.658
If it is Raydor,
who's gonna replace her?

21:00.660 --> 21:01.926
Well,
maybe it'll be you.

21:01.928 --> 21:04.528
[ Scoffs ] Not me.
Not as a lieutenant.

21:04.530 --> 21:08.399
Although, Cooper's a lieutenant
and he runs SIS.

21:08.401 --> 21:10.434
Or maybe
they'll make you a captain.

21:10.436 --> 21:12.670
Oh, God, I don't want
to be a captain.

21:12.672 --> 21:14.705
All those extra
damn meetings.

21:14.707 --> 21:19.277
No, I think just listening to
people call me Captain

21:19.279 --> 21:21.979
instead of Lieutenant
would be like...

21:25.251 --> 21:27.985
would be like
changing my name.

21:29.689 --> 21:33.624
Fred: It wasn't an easy process
or a quick one either.

21:33.626 --> 21:36.494
It took three months for
all the paperwork to go through,

21:36.496 --> 21:38.963
and meanwhile, we were
just trying to deal,

21:38.965 --> 21:40.097
God, with everything.

21:40.099 --> 21:41.465
What was everything?

21:41.467 --> 21:43.701
Keeping
our old credit rating

21:43.703 --> 21:46.570
while trying to sell our house
in the Palisades

21:46.572 --> 21:48.606
and buy a new one
in Pasadena.

21:48.608 --> 21:50.941
Getting our medical records
synched up

21:50.943 --> 21:55.179
and coping with...
our son's trauma.

21:55.181 --> 21:57.682
It was like,
to a certain extent,

21:57.684 --> 22:00.217
living in the, uh,
witness protection program.

22:00.219 --> 22:01.752
Here, Zora.

22:01.754 --> 22:05.656
Would you mind telling us Will's
name before the accident...

22:05.658 --> 22:07.425
-How old he was.
-...and how old he was.

22:07.427 --> 22:10.895
Ye gods.
They're becoming telepathic.

22:10.897 --> 22:12.930
<i> His name was Malik.</i>

22:12.932 --> 22:17.902
<i> M-a-l-i-k.</i>

22:17.904 --> 22:20.037
Malik Jacob Lewis.

22:20.039 --> 22:23.240
<i> He was, uh,</i>
<i> just 16 1/2 years old.</i>

22:23.242 --> 22:24.909
I'm curious.

22:24.911 --> 22:27.778
Lots of people have accidents
and keep their name,

22:27.780 --> 22:32.116
but you found it necessary
to change yours. Why?

22:32.118 --> 22:36.654
To avoid the scrutiny that would
follow Will his whole life.

22:36.656 --> 22:38.289
One Google search
is all it would take

22:38.291 --> 22:39.990
to bring up the news stories,

22:39.992 --> 22:47.365
and...we thought
the whole experience was...

22:47.367 --> 22:50.167
What happened to that, uh,

22:50.169 --> 22:54.538
that boy Will ran over,
that was terrible.

22:54.540 --> 22:56.040
But it was not
our son's fault.

22:56.042 --> 23:00.678
And he was absolved of
any criminal or civil blame?

23:00.680 --> 23:02.980
<i> I mean,</i>
<i> there was no trials or --</i>

23:02.982 --> 23:06.350
<i> Nothing. It was clearly</i>
<i> the other boy's mistake.</i>

23:06.352 --> 23:08.152
Hey, here we go,
Lieutenant.

23:08.154 --> 23:10.087
April 20, 2009.

23:10.089 --> 23:12.423
Malik Lewis was involved in
a one-car accident

23:12.425 --> 23:14.625
with a parked vehicle
that resulted in a fatality.

23:14.627 --> 23:15.926
Looking for a victim,
sir.

23:15.928 --> 23:17.928
Okay.
Make sure that the Captain gets

23:17.930 --> 23:21.365
the full SCID report
on this accident.
I'm on it, sir.

23:21.367 --> 23:24.668
<i> Will often went to</i>
<i> the boy's grave with flowers.</i>

23:24.670 --> 23:26.537
And he prayed there
sometimes.

23:26.539 --> 23:30.007
Our son dedicated his life
to what was

23:30.009 --> 23:32.510
<i> essentially</i>
<i> an act of penance</i>

23:32.512 --> 23:34.912
<i> for the death</i>
<i> of that other boy.</i>

23:34.914 --> 23:37.148
Well, looks like revenge
is suddenly back on the board.

23:37.150 --> 23:40.918
Revenge has always been
my favorite motive.

23:40.920 --> 23:43.621
<i> We did everything we could</i>
<i> to protect him.</i>

23:43.623 --> 23:46.023
It's just unbelievable

23:46.025 --> 23:49.360
that he could die
in an accident like this.

23:49.362 --> 23:53.564
It's just unbelievable.

23:54.400 --> 23:57.168
Yes, it is.

23:57.170 --> 24:00.938
Malik Lewis was a junior
at Andrews Prep in Santa Monica.

24:00.940 --> 24:04.241
Great grades, debate team,
baseball, girlfriend.

24:04.243 --> 24:05.576
Was a pretty happy kid.

24:05.578 --> 24:07.678
And then one day
driving home from school,

24:07.680 --> 24:10.848
Malik Lewis swerved to avoid
hitting an 18-year-old kid,

24:10.850 --> 24:13.751
Kevin Harris, chasing a Frisbee
into the street.

24:13.753 --> 24:16.754
Now, Malik's reflexes
weren't so quick.

24:16.756 --> 24:19.924
He ended up slamming Harris
into a parked car,

24:19.926 --> 24:23.594
smashing him between his BMW
and another vehicle, sir.

24:23.596 --> 24:25.996
[ Door opens ]
Sorry I'm late.

24:25.998 --> 24:28.999
Uh, did you find the old autopsy
we were looking for?

24:29.001 --> 24:30.234
Thank you.

24:30.236 --> 24:32.369
And I also have the PET
color scan to go with it.

24:32.371 --> 24:34.271
Kind of gruesome.
Where are you?

24:34.273 --> 24:38.876
Uh, where Kevin Harris was held
in place between two cars.

24:38.878 --> 24:42.012
And Malik Lewis
jumped out of his vehicle

24:42.014 --> 24:44.682
and stood face to face
with Kevin Harris

24:44.684 --> 24:46.250
for a few minutes
as he died.

24:46.252 --> 24:49.553
Firefighters and paramedics
arrived to free Harris,

24:49.555 --> 24:50.988
but they were too late,
sir.

24:50.990 --> 24:52.723
He might as well
have died on impact.

24:52.725 --> 24:55.259
Kevin
was almost in two pieces.

24:55.261 --> 24:57.528
Uh, shattered his spleen,

24:57.530 --> 25:00.731
two broken vertebra,
ruptured liver.

25:00.733 --> 25:02.733
He talked briefly
with one of the EMTs,

25:02.735 --> 25:05.269
whose tears you can see
on his report.

25:05.271 --> 25:06.504
You did the autopsy?

25:06.506 --> 25:08.005
Yes, but it wasn't
a big mystery.

25:08.007 --> 25:10.241
There was the physical evidence
and the witnesses,

25:10.243 --> 25:12.643
and the hardest thing was taking
him into the viewing room

25:12.645 --> 25:14.712
for his I.D.,
which the mother demanded.

25:14.714 --> 25:16.013
Couldn't believe
what had happened.

25:16.015 --> 25:17.781
The two officers
from Traffic said

25:17.783 --> 25:19.483
it was one of the hardest
notifications they'd ever done,

25:19.485 --> 25:22.019
and they don't do anything
but notify people every day.

25:22.021 --> 25:25.055
What a horrible job. Can't think
why anyone would want it.

25:25.057 --> 25:27.791
And now we get to
the connection.

25:27.793 --> 25:30.861
Kevin Harris' mom,
Joanne Harris --

25:30.863 --> 25:32.930
Sanchez: Owns a framing shop
on the Westside.

25:32.932 --> 25:35.199
Address shows she hasn't moved
since the accident.

25:35.201 --> 25:38.435
Flynn: And she has two vehicles
registered to her name.

25:38.437 --> 25:41.372
One is
a 2006 Chevy Tahoe.

25:41.374 --> 25:43.607
Which fits the make
of the headlight piece.

25:43.609 --> 25:45.009
And you think all this
gives you a warrant?

25:45.011 --> 25:47.778
We already have one.
But we may not need to use it.

25:47.780 --> 25:49.547
Great.
Terrific.

25:49.549 --> 25:51.048
I release a statement saying

25:51.050 --> 25:53.918
we were going after hit and runs
more seriously.

25:53.920 --> 25:55.119
We are.

25:55.121 --> 25:56.654
Much more seriously.

25:56.656 --> 26:00.057
We're sorry to bother you,
Mrs. Harris.

26:00.059 --> 26:04.028
I know it's rather late in
the day to drop by unannounced.

26:04.030 --> 26:06.597
No, you're not interrupting
anything at all.

26:06.599 --> 26:09.366
You said that
this is a follow-up

26:09.368 --> 26:10.534
to the death of my son?

26:10.536 --> 26:11.869
Fairly routine.

26:11.871 --> 26:13.571
We're reviewing old cases
to determine

26:13.573 --> 26:15.773
if procedure was followed
to the letter.

26:15.775 --> 26:17.708
Your son's file
was high on the list.

26:17.710 --> 26:19.977
Even though
no one was arrested?

26:19.979 --> 26:22.313
Especially because
no one was arrested.

26:23.382 --> 26:25.583
That's
a handsome young man.

26:25.585 --> 26:27.985
Yes, he was.

26:28.955 --> 26:31.055
W-Would you like to
see his room?

26:31.057 --> 26:34.158
♪♪

26:37.697 --> 26:39.597
He was planning on
being a magician.

26:39.599 --> 26:41.999
[ Sighs ]

26:42.001 --> 26:45.636
He was already working
the children's birthday parties.

26:45.638 --> 26:48.305
He loved little kids.

26:48.307 --> 26:52.009
I come in here whenever I want
to spend time with him.

26:56.115 --> 26:57.314
Nothing much, sir.

26:57.316 --> 26:59.383
A brand-new Toyota
parked at the curb.

26:59.385 --> 27:00.718
It's registered to her.

27:00.720 --> 27:02.453
No sign of the Tahoe.

27:02.455 --> 27:03.887
I wonder why.

27:03.889 --> 27:05.155
Oil stain on the driveway,

27:05.157 --> 27:06.824
like someone
normally parks there.

27:06.826 --> 27:10.361
Probably didn't come from
her brand-new car.

27:10.363 --> 27:11.862
Mama Harris.

27:11.864 --> 27:15.165
[ Chuckles ]
What did you do?

27:15.167 --> 27:18.068
He was preparing for
his very first magic show

27:18.070 --> 27:21.205
with people from the
Magic Castle coming to see him.

27:21.207 --> 27:23.874
Two days before he died.

27:23.876 --> 27:26.577
Run down in the street
by some careless driver.

27:26.579 --> 27:28.879
I'm so sorry.

27:30.316 --> 27:32.049
Accidents happen.

27:32.051 --> 27:36.487
They happen, and as time
goes by, we move on.

27:36.489 --> 27:38.822
That's what
everybody said.

27:38.824 --> 27:40.891
But everybody was wrong.

27:40.893 --> 27:45.229
[ Voice breaking ]
Because when you lose a child...

27:45.231 --> 27:47.931
time does not go by.

27:50.002 --> 27:52.269
It just comes to
a dead halt.

27:56.275 --> 28:00.077
You said the driver who ran over
your son was careless.

28:00.079 --> 28:02.279
Of course.
[ Sniffles ]

28:02.281 --> 28:04.114
How else
could it have happened?

28:04.116 --> 28:05.683
But he wasn't
prosecuted.

28:05.685 --> 28:07.985
No. No.

28:07.987 --> 28:10.320
You people
and the insurance company

28:10.322 --> 28:12.623
said that
the boy wasn't liable.

28:12.625 --> 28:14.658
So his parents picked him up

28:14.660 --> 28:17.361
in their Porsche SUV
and drove him off.

28:17.363 --> 28:20.898
And I guess he just
went on with his life.

28:21.934 --> 28:24.134
She's still in
a great deal of pain.

28:24.136 --> 28:26.303
But capable
of killing someone?

28:26.305 --> 28:27.538
I don't know.

28:27.540 --> 28:30.207
Her Tahoe was missing,
and it fits with the headlight.

28:30.209 --> 28:32.242
If she used it
to murder Will, sir,

28:32.244 --> 28:34.144
she could be
getting body work done.

28:34.146 --> 28:36.447
Too bad we can't just ask her
who her mechanic is.

28:37.983 --> 28:40.150
Maybe we won't have to.

28:40.152 --> 28:43.253
♪♪

29:10.783 --> 29:12.049
Show off.

29:12.051 --> 29:13.550
It's more fun when
you got a court order

29:13.552 --> 29:14.952
giving you permission.

29:20.359 --> 29:21.959
[ Device beeps ]

29:29.268 --> 29:31.401
[ Clears throat ]

29:31.403 --> 29:33.270
Don't tell Patrice.

29:33.272 --> 29:36.073
No offense, Lieutenant, but that
anchovy and garlic smell...

29:36.075 --> 29:39.309
Hey, this is
a stakeout tradition, Buzz.

29:39.311 --> 29:41.278
Anchovies, garlic.

29:41.280 --> 29:43.046
Mmm.
Keeps you up.

29:43.048 --> 29:44.448
[ Chuckles ]
[ Door opens ]

29:44.450 --> 29:47.684
Oh, Lieutenant.
How'd you catch the night shift?

29:47.686 --> 29:52.723
Oh, well, Tao is headed to,
uh, his Hollywood job.

29:52.725 --> 29:54.324
Going on location.

29:54.326 --> 29:58.328
And Sanchez, well, he likes to
tuck the kid in at night.

29:58.330 --> 30:00.297
Little Mark.

30:00.299 --> 30:01.999
[ Chuckles ]

30:02.001 --> 30:03.467
Think this'll work?

30:03.469 --> 30:04.768
Sure, why not?

30:04.770 --> 30:06.069
She'll come out
in the morning,

30:06.071 --> 30:07.805
she'll see her car
has been vandalized.

30:07.807 --> 30:10.874
She'll go to the repairman,
we'll find the other car,

30:10.876 --> 30:12.442
and presto change-o,

30:12.444 --> 30:17.648
Captain Sharon Raydor
is the new Assistant Chief.

30:17.650 --> 30:21.218
Okay,
mark this day, people.

30:21.220 --> 30:23.821
This could be
the end of an era.

30:23.823 --> 30:28.458
My last stakeout pizza ever.

30:30.663 --> 30:32.429
Mmm.

30:32.431 --> 30:34.464
Mmm.

30:40.706 --> 30:42.706
Oh, is, uh,
that about Stroh?

30:42.708 --> 30:44.374
Fritz gave it to me.

30:44.376 --> 30:46.210
It's another connection.

30:46.212 --> 30:48.212
First his sixth-grade
science teacher

30:48.214 --> 30:50.113
gets electrocuted
in Pittsburgh,

30:50.115 --> 30:52.249
and then
his high-school girlfriend

30:52.251 --> 30:54.318
is found drowned
in her backyard pool,

30:54.320 --> 30:57.654
and now an ex-professor
from Ann Arbor

30:57.656 --> 31:00.190
seems to have shot himself.

31:00.192 --> 31:03.660
Lots of people who knew Stroh
have probably died.

31:03.662 --> 31:05.529
Why would he
come back here?

31:05.531 --> 31:07.497
Just to settle old scores?

31:09.235 --> 31:10.734
Are you seriously worried?

31:10.736 --> 31:12.269
Fritz is.

31:12.271 --> 31:16.907
And as far as assigning rational
motives to Stroh's behavior,

31:16.909 --> 31:20.077
he's psychotic, Andy...
[ Door opens ]

31:20.079 --> 31:21.945
...and we know
he carries a grudge.

31:21.947 --> 31:23.213
[ Sighs ]

31:23.215 --> 31:25.716
I don't think
I look my age.

31:25.718 --> 31:28.018
Maybe I should
grow a goatee.

31:28.020 --> 31:29.920
Yeah, but how many years
would that take?

31:29.922 --> 31:32.389
Probably two
if I started right now.

31:32.391 --> 31:34.524
Oh, um, Wes and Hobbs

31:34.526 --> 31:37.294
nailed another defendant
in court the other day.

31:37.296 --> 31:39.463
You guys would've been
really proud of them.

31:41.166 --> 31:43.567
What, do I look weird? My --
My hair, it feels funny today.

31:43.569 --> 31:45.736
No, I'm just thinking
you're almost 21

31:45.738 --> 31:47.337
and how grown up you are.

31:47.339 --> 31:49.606
Well, I-I know
you don't want the job,

31:49.608 --> 31:52.609
but, um, good luck with
your interview today, Mom.

31:52.611 --> 31:54.645
Thank you.

31:58.784 --> 32:00.951
You going down?
I'll go with you.

32:00.953 --> 32:02.419
Andy.

32:02.421 --> 32:04.421
Yeah, I'll grab my car
in just a second.

32:04.423 --> 32:07.958
I have a few more things I need
to take care of before I leave.

32:10.796 --> 32:12.162
Provenza:
Okay, here we go.

32:12.164 --> 32:14.298
Wake up, Sykes.
[ Tapping ]

32:14.300 --> 32:16.600
-About to have some action.
-I'm up.

32:18.904 --> 32:19.970
All right.

32:19.972 --> 32:21.438
[ Car alarm chirps ]

32:21.440 --> 32:24.541
♪♪

32:32.351 --> 32:35.118
Okay.
Now, with any luck,

32:35.120 --> 32:37.187
she'll drive us
straight to the murder weapon,

32:37.189 --> 32:39.790
and we'll be eating omelettes
in an hour.

32:39.792 --> 32:41.558
Come on.

32:45.064 --> 32:47.397
So, ready for your turn
under the heat lamp?

32:47.399 --> 32:49.066
As ready
as I'll ever be.

32:49.068 --> 32:50.600
Give you a little tip.

32:50.602 --> 32:52.636
Chief's gonna ask what you see
is the biggest problem

32:52.638 --> 32:55.872
confronting the future
of the LAPD, but...

32:55.874 --> 32:58.008
it's a trick question.
-Oh?

32:58.010 --> 32:59.476
You may want to
say terrorism,

32:59.478 --> 33:01.645
you may want to say
cyber attacks,

33:01.647 --> 33:03.313
but that's all bullshit.

33:03.315 --> 33:05.315
What he wants to know
really

33:05.317 --> 33:06.583
is what's your
biggest problem

33:06.585 --> 33:08.585
with the way
the department's organized.

33:08.587 --> 33:11.154
What would Sharon Raydor do
differently than Russell Taylor

33:11.156 --> 33:13.023
as Assistant
Chief of Operations?

33:13.025 --> 33:14.524
Are you sure
that's what they want,

33:14.526 --> 33:16.259
or is that
just what you did?

33:16.261 --> 33:18.595
No, I talked about terrorism
and cyber stuff.

33:18.597 --> 33:19.796
[ Laughs ]

33:19.798 --> 33:21.131
And they reminded me

33:21.133 --> 33:22.532
that we have whole divisions
devoted to that

33:22.534 --> 33:24.534
and asked how
I would deploy them.

33:24.536 --> 33:27.637
So skip my mistake
and explain your process

33:27.639 --> 33:31.174
and concentrate on how the LAPD
needs a leader in that office.

33:31.176 --> 33:32.642
-Such as you.
-Or you.

33:32.644 --> 33:34.745
Hey, I'm really young.

33:34.747 --> 33:36.446
And really ambitious.

33:36.448 --> 33:39.716
I'm not saying otherwise,
Captain, but I can wait.

33:39.718 --> 33:42.185
And I like my life
the way it is, you know?

33:42.187 --> 33:44.054
Yeah, I do.

33:44.056 --> 33:45.589
I really do.

33:45.591 --> 33:47.357
[ Cellphone ringing ]

33:47.960 --> 33:51.161
Okay, we have progress.

33:52.231 --> 33:54.031
Good morning, Lieutenant.

33:54.033 --> 33:56.099
-She's on the move, Captain.
-Very good.

33:56.101 --> 33:57.801
Bring everyone in
carefully.

33:57.803 --> 33:59.202
We don't want to spook her.

33:59.204 --> 34:01.071
I'll meet you as agreed.

34:03.275 --> 34:05.042
[ Tools whirring ]

34:05.044 --> 34:08.345
♪♪

34:27.199 --> 34:29.566
[ Indistinct conversation ]

34:36.375 --> 34:38.508
Sanchez: Ms. Harris,
stay right where you are.

34:43.015 --> 34:44.781
Sir.

34:46.185 --> 34:48.685
Lieutenant, got it.

34:53.158 --> 34:55.125
[ Clears throat ]

34:57.296 --> 34:58.528
Is this your car,
ma'am?

34:58.530 --> 35:01.665
Why?
What does it matter?

35:03.001 --> 35:05.435
LAPD.
You need to come with us.

35:05.437 --> 35:07.070
You have the right...

35:07.072 --> 35:08.305
Captain,
they're on their way.

35:08.307 --> 35:09.673
Anything you say can

35:09.675 --> 35:11.441
and will be used against you
in a court of law.

35:11.443 --> 35:13.577
Can you put the wheels back on,
lower the car, please?

35:13.579 --> 35:15.545
-I'm not done with it.
-Yes, you are.

35:15.547 --> 35:17.180
Have you heard
and understood these rights

35:17.182 --> 35:19.116
as they have been
read to you?

35:19.118 --> 35:22.419
♪♪

35:29.795 --> 35:31.061
Where are we going?

35:31.063 --> 35:34.131
To the scene of
an accident, ma'am.

35:50.983 --> 35:52.516
Thank you.

35:54.186 --> 35:58.021
Mrs. Harris,
I'm Captain Sharon Raydor.

35:58.023 --> 36:02.392
I see
these fresh flowers.

36:02.394 --> 36:06.396
Did you place them here recently
for Kevin?

36:06.398 --> 36:07.898
I'm not going to ask you

36:07.900 --> 36:11.968
because I already know
why you ran Will Sax down.

36:11.970 --> 36:13.570
We all understand.

36:13.572 --> 36:18.341
What I can't figure out is
how you were able to locate him.

36:20.112 --> 36:23.747
Mrs. Harris,
we're seriously good detectives,

36:23.749 --> 36:27.417
but we didn't find out that
Malik Lewis and his whole family

36:27.419 --> 36:31.655
had changed their names
until his mom and dad told us.

36:31.657 --> 36:36.726
But somehow, some way,
you were able to find him.

36:36.728 --> 36:38.195
Is that correct?

36:39.665 --> 36:41.798
No.

36:41.800 --> 36:44.434
He found me.

36:45.437 --> 36:48.305
To say that, "I'm so sorry
your son is dead."

36:49.374 --> 36:52.242
That's what Malik wrote to me
in his letter.

36:52.244 --> 36:54.744
Will wrote you, ma'am?

36:54.746 --> 36:57.614
To apologize.

36:57.616 --> 37:01.451
To say that he --
say that he grieved with me.

37:01.453 --> 37:04.754
That he thought about Kevin
every day.

37:04.756 --> 37:06.156
[ Sniffles ]

37:06.158 --> 37:10.794
And that how the last words
that he shared with Kevin...

37:10.796 --> 37:14.197
were going to transform his life
forever.

37:14.199 --> 37:17.968
That's --
that's what my son died for.

37:17.970 --> 37:23.707
Malik's transformation
into Will Sax, the hero.

37:23.709 --> 37:26.376
How did you know
he was a hero?

37:26.378 --> 37:29.045
I found him on Facebook.

37:29.047 --> 37:31.815
You know, I got all caught up
in his life.

37:31.817 --> 37:34.618
He was about to clerk
for a federal judge.

37:34.620 --> 37:37.320
He was engaged
to be married.

37:37.322 --> 37:42.592
He had
such a bright future.

37:42.594 --> 37:45.695
♪♪

37:50.902 --> 37:52.936
[ Sobs ]

37:52.938 --> 37:56.706
But there was
no mention of Kevin.

37:56.708 --> 37:58.308
Not a word.

37:58.310 --> 37:59.743
No account anywhere

37:59.745 --> 38:02.412
of the so-called
transformational sacrifice

38:02.414 --> 38:04.848
that my son made
on his behalf.

38:04.850 --> 38:09.819
So much for thinking about
my little boy every day.

38:12.291 --> 38:17.093
You might find it strange
that I just couldn't let it go,

38:17.095 --> 38:19.529
that I needed to
even the scales.

38:19.531 --> 38:22.032
No.
No, no, I don't.

38:22.034 --> 38:23.566
I don't find it strange.

38:23.568 --> 38:26.770
I find it instructive.

38:28.907 --> 38:30.974
[ Sighs ]

38:30.976 --> 38:33.943
So, you can call it murder
if you'd like.

38:33.945 --> 38:36.446
I call it justice,

38:36.448 --> 38:38.148
and I think a jury
will agree with me.

38:38.150 --> 38:44.421
Well, we will certainly help you
test your theory.

38:46.525 --> 38:51.428
Ma'am, you're under arrest
for the murder of Will Sax.

38:52.497 --> 38:55.298
There is
no such person.

38:55.300 --> 38:58.568
♪♪

39:09.314 --> 39:10.680
[ Horn honks ]

39:10.682 --> 39:11.981
Found the letter Will wrote
to Kevin's mother,

39:11.983 --> 39:13.683
plus I dropped off her computer
at cyber.

39:13.685 --> 39:15.585
History showed
she must've spent hours

39:15.587 --> 39:18.154
tracking him online
for the past month.

39:18.156 --> 39:21.057
Tons of photos of Will
synched from her phone.

39:21.059 --> 39:24.227
You put that together
with the Tahoe...Phew.

39:24.229 --> 39:26.129
Buzz: I wonder if she'll still
feel good about

39:26.131 --> 39:28.498
killing Will Sax
the day her trial starts.

39:28.500 --> 39:30.567
Sykes:
Or the day she dies in prison.

39:30.569 --> 39:32.235
If she even
makes it that far.

39:32.237 --> 39:34.537
To me, she looked like
someone ready to call it quits.

39:34.539 --> 39:36.506
Well,
better late than never.

39:36.508 --> 39:38.842
If you'll excuse me.

39:41.613 --> 39:43.480
[ Knock on door ]
-Yes.

39:43.482 --> 39:45.181
Captain,
you have a second?

39:45.183 --> 39:47.083
Uh, one, Lieutenant.

39:48.153 --> 39:49.652
Is there a problem?

39:49.654 --> 39:53.523
Oh, no. The case looks good,
as do you, by the way.

39:53.525 --> 39:55.492
You look like a winner.

39:55.494 --> 39:58.395
Hope you save the department
from Winnie Davis.

39:58.397 --> 39:59.696
If it wasn't for Winnie,

39:59.698 --> 40:01.131
I wouldn't be going
in this interview,

40:01.133 --> 40:04.267
but if there have to be changes
around here, then...

40:04.269 --> 40:06.302
Well, yes.

40:06.304 --> 40:08.037
There has to be change.

40:09.174 --> 40:10.473
Which is why I --

40:10.475 --> 40:13.109
For example, what if
the unimaginable happened

40:13.111 --> 40:15.712
and I was to become
Assistant Chief?

40:15.714 --> 40:21.184
Well, Captain, that's --
that's not unimaginable at all.

40:21.186 --> 40:25.255
Well, then there would be
this 16x22-foot office

40:25.257 --> 40:30.160
that would need redesigning
to match your promotion.

40:30.162 --> 40:33.797
Oh, don't worry, I'm sure that
Patrice will help you out.

40:33.799 --> 40:35.598
[ Chuckling ] Oh, yeah.
She would.

40:35.600 --> 40:37.400
[ Chuckles ]
Well...

40:37.402 --> 40:38.735
[ Chuckles ]

40:38.737 --> 40:40.537
Thank you, Captain.

40:40.539 --> 40:43.706
I am
deeply appreciative.

40:43.708 --> 40:46.176
[ Chuckles ]
I mean...

40:46.178 --> 40:47.377
[ Clears throat ]

40:47.379 --> 40:49.913
I mean...

40:49.915 --> 40:52.649
I am very, very glad

40:52.651 --> 40:55.752
to have so much
of your confidence.

40:55.754 --> 40:58.922
And my affection,
Lieutenant.

41:02.327 --> 41:04.861
Whether you want it
or not.

41:07.999 --> 41:09.566
Look around, Louie.

41:09.568 --> 41:13.169
I've always loved
the view.

41:13.171 --> 41:15.505
[ Chuckles ]

41:15.507 --> 41:18.808
♪♪

41:26.084 --> 41:28.551
[ Sighs ]

41:35.193 --> 41:38.495
♪♪
